			<h1><span class="less"><a href="index.html">SLE 2018</a> paper:</span><br><i>Analysing meta-model product lines</i></h1>
			<h2><a href="../profile/EstherGuerra.html">Esther Guerra</a>, <a href="../profile/JuandeLara.html">Juan de Lara</a>, <a href="../profile/MarshaChechik.html">Marsha Chechik</a>, <a href="../profile/RickSalay.html">Rick Salay</a></h2>
<ul><li>DOI: <a href="https://doi.org/10.1145/3276604.3276609">10.1145/3276604.3276609</a></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t1a.html"><span class="tagM">T1A: Design</span></a><ul><li> The paper primarily contributes techniques for language definition (often syntax-related) as part of language design.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t5d.html"><span class="tagL">T5D: Formal Methods</span></a><ul><li> It relies on formal methods (definitions/proofs/semantic properties) beyond informal description.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t2c.html"><span class="tagL">T2C: Variability</span></a><ul><li> It targets product lines/variability (feature models, variability, configuration).
</li></ul></li></ul>
